\chapter{Truncated and connected types}
%\textcite{Shulman-logic-of-space}

\section{Motivation 1: Understanding types better}

We assume that the reader knows the basics of Martin-Löf's dependent type theory
(MLTT) with the usual type formers such as dependent sums $(a : A) \times B(a)$,
dependent products $(a : A) \to B(a)$, identity types $a=_Ab$, empty type $0$,
unit type $1$, coproducts $A+B$, natural numbers type $\NN$, and universes
$\UU$. If not, good references that also go in the direction of synthetic
homotopy theory include~\textcite{Rijke2022,hottbook}.

MLTT can be used both as a programming language and as a foundation for mathematics. For the latter, the idea is to use the propositions as types paradigm, according to which universal quantification $\forall a:A, B(a)$ can be encoded as the dependent product $(a:A) \to B(a)$, existential quantification $\exists a:A, B(a)$ as the dependent sum $(a:A) \times B(a)$, and disjunction $A \vee B$ as the coproduct $A + B$.
But this translation does not give an adequate formalization of many mathematical concepts, as the following example illustrates.

Consider a function $f : A \to B$. Intuitively, we would express the
\emph{image} of $f$ as the subtype of $B$ consisting of those $b:B$ for which
there exists $a:A$ with $f(a)=_Bb$. According the above translation, this becomes the type
\[(b:B)\times(a:A)\times(f(a)=_Bb)\]
consisting of triples $(b,a,p)$ where $b:B$, $a:A$ and $p:f(a)=_Bb$.
Using the principle of function extensionality (which is not provable in MLTT, but needs to be assumed in order to capture the mathematical practice of identifying functions $f,g : (a:A) \to B(a)$ when we have identification $h(a):f(a)=_{B(a)}g(a)$ for all $a:A$),
it turns out (see below), that this type of triples can be identified with the type $A$ via the projection to the second factor. (The inverse maps $a:A$ to the triple $(f(a), a, \refl_a)$.)

In other words, this definition of the image is not correct. A related example
is the formalization that a function $f : A \to B$ is a \emph{surjection} via
the proposition
\[\forall b:B, \exists a:A, f(a) =_B b.\]
According to the above translation, this becomes the type
\[(b:B) \to (a:A)\times(f(a)=_B b).\]
However, if we have an element $s$ of this type, we can compose with the first projection
to get a function $g : B \to A$ such that $f(g(b))=_Bb$ for all $b:B$, i.e.,
a section of $f$.
But the statement that every surjection has a section is equivalent to the axiom of choice, and we want to be free to assume this or not, if we're doing constructive mathematics.

The solution to these problems became apparent with the advent of \emph{Univalent Foundations}: Here we realize that all types have a built-in homotopical structure that we can probe with the identity types. For instance, mathematical propositions are not any old types, but types $A$ in which any two elements can be identified, i.e., for which we have a function $p:(a,b:A) \to a=_Ab$. And then we need a new type former, \emph{propositional truncation}, $\Trunc\blank$, that associates to any type $A$ a proposition $\Trunc A$. Then the correct definition of the image becomes
\[\im(f) := (b : B) \times \Trunc{(a:A) \times (f(a)=_B b)},\]
and the correct definition of being surjective becomes
\[\isSurj(f) := (b : B) \to \Trunc{(a:A) \times (f(a)=_Bb)}.\]
That is, the correct interpretation of a general existential proposition $\exists a:A, B(a)$ is the truncation of the dependent sum, $\Trunc{(a:A)\times B(a)}$.

Propositional truncation also solves the problem of how to express quotients in type theory.

One motivation for studying \emph{synthetic homotopy theory} is to better
understand this higher structure of types as probed by the identity types, and
to understand the identity types various types, how to exploit the higher
structure in the formalization of mathematics, and to develop tools for dealing
with truncations and its higher-dimensional cousins.

\section{Motivation 2: Homotopy groups of spheres}

The univalent foundations interpretation of type theory also suggests new type formers,
so-called \emph{higher inductive types} (HITs). The most basic example is the (homotopical) circle, which we'll return to below. We'll see that many HITs can be defined in terms of pushouts. This is not too surprising, as any colimit can be expressed via (infinite) coproducts and pushouts (or coequalizers). In type theory, we can express pullbacks via identity types, so it's natural to want to have a type former for pushouts.

Using HITs built from pushouts, we suddenly have access to all the (homotopical)
spheres $S^n$, along with their homotopy groups $\pi_k(S^n)$. These are famous
characters in a long-running story (classical \emph{analysis situs}, algebraic
topology, homotopy theory). See~\cref{tab:pi-k-s-n} for a small
sample. Mathematicians have expended a lot of effort trying to understand the
patterns in these groups, and they have come up with a lot of clever tools,
including long exact sequences, homology and cohomology theories (and their
operations), spectral sequences, and higher category theory
($(\infty,1)$-category theory) along the way. Many of these have been ported to
type theory, although the definition of $(\infty,1)$-categories has so far
eluded us. (Many even think it's impossible to capture higher categories with
the type formers mentioned so far, but this has also not been proved.)

