So a second motivation for studying synthetic homotopy theory is to understand the tools of classical homotopy theory from the point of view of type theory, trying to generalize them so they're no longer tied to classical axioms such as the axiom of choice, and to push the boundaries of what we can express with type theory.

We shall develop enough material to understand the first row, why the next two rows agree for $k\ge 4$, why there are zeros under the diagonal, and why $\pi_3(S^2)\simeq \ZZ$.

\paragraph{A note on terminology}
We use \emph{univalent foundations} (UF) for the general program of developing mathematics with the univalence axiom, paying close attention to the identifications in and between various types. It is compatible with both classical and constructive mathematics, where we view the former as a special case of the latter where we assume the general axiom of choice (which also implies the law of excluded middle). \emph{Homotopy type theory} (HoTT) is to be understood in analogy with \emph{set theory} as studying both formal systems for implementing UF (typically type theories), as well how to formalize mathematical notions and proofs in these systems. Book HoTT is a particular choice of formal system, corresponding to that employed in~\textcite{hottbook}. Cubical type theories are newer formal systems adapted to UF where the univalence axiom is provable from more primitive ingredients so that they directly function as programming languages. Since the resolution of Voevoedsky's homotopy canonicity conjecture, book HoTT can also be used as a programming language.

\section{Homotopical notions in type theory}

We begin our journey into synthetic homotopy theory by translating the notions of truncatedness and connectedness into type theory.
We also introduce the algebra of paths in type theory, and show how it can be used to define homotopy groups of types.

\begin{definition}
    A type $X$ is \textbf{contractible} if we have an inhabitant of the type
    \[ \isContr(X) := (x : X) \times ((y : X) \to x =_X y). \]
    A type $X$ is a \textbf{proposition} if we have an inhabitant of
    \[ \isProp(X) := (x, y : X) \to x =_X y.\]
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}
  A map $f : X \to Y$ is an \textbf{equivalence} if for all $y : Y$ we have $\fib_f(y)$ is contractible, where $\fib_f(y) := (x:X)\times(f(x)=_Yy)$ is the \textbf{homotopy fiber} of $f$ at $y$. (Which we met above when discussing images and surjections.)

  The \textbf{type of equivalences} from $X$ to $Y$ is the dependent sum
  \[ (X \simeq Y) := (X \to Y) \times \isEquiv(f).\]
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}
  The \textbf{univalence axiom} states that for every universe $\UU$, the map
  \[
    (X=_\UU Y) \to (X \simeq Y),
    \quad
    \refl_X \mapsto (\id_X, \_),
  \]
  is an equivalence.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
  In the following we always assume univalence. It implies function extensionality: the map
  \[ (f =_{(x:X) \to Y(x)} g) \to \Bigl((x:X) \to f(x)=_{Y(x)}g(x)\Bigr),
    \quad
    \refl_f \mapsto (x \mapsto \refl_{f(x)}),
  \]
  from \textbf{homotopies} to paths is an equivalence. We shall use both
  freely, going between equivalences and homotopies and the corresponding
  identifications.
\end{remark}

\begin{definition}
    We can define a stratification of types which begins with contractible types and then propositions by recursion. For a type $X$ we say:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item $X$ is a \textbf{$-2$-type} if it is contractible.
        \item $X$ is a \textbf{$-1$-type} if it is a proposition.
        \item $X$ is an\textbf{ $n$-type} if for all $x, y : X$ the type $x=_Xy$ is an $n-1$ type.
    \end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
    We call $0$-types sets and $1$-types groupoids. These correspond exactly to the usual notions!
    This also explains the indexing, as sets are ``$0$-dimensional'' objects. But it's also natural to use an indexing where contractible types are at level $0$: This hierarchy is called the h-level (homotopy level) hierarchy, so a type is \textbf{of hlevel $n+2$} if and only if it is an $n$-type.
\end{remark}

\begin{example}
We give some basic examples of $n$-types.
\begin{itemize}
\item The only $-2$-type is the unit type $1$. More precisely, the type of
  $-2$-types is contractible.
    \item $-1$-types are subtypes of $1$. For example the empty type $0$.
    \item The type of integers $\ZZ$ is a $0$-type. More generally any (non higher) inductive type is a $0$-type.
    \item The type of $n$-types in a universe $\UU$, $\UU^{\le n}$, is an $n+1$ type, for $n\ge-1$.
    \item Any $n$-type is also an $(n+1)$-type
\end{itemize}
\end{example}

\begin{definition}
    There is a \textbf{truncation} operation for each $n$ which takes a type $X$ to an $n$-type version of itself in a natural way.
    We do not define it here, however we present its universal property, which is all that's needed to work with it.

    Given a type $X$, its \textbf{$n$-truncation} is a type $\Trunc{X}_n$.
    It comes with a map $\trunc{\blank}_n : X \to \Trunc{X}_n$ such that for any $n$-type $Y$, and any map $X \to Y$, there is a unique map $\Trunc{X}_n \to Y$ so that
    \[\begin{tikzcd}
        X  \ar[r] \ar[d, swap, "\trunc{\blank}_n"] & Y \\
        \Trunc{X}_n \ar[ur,dashed]
      \end{tikzcd}\] commutes. Equivalently, the map
    $\blank\circ\trunc\blank_n : (\Trunc X_n \to Y) \to (X \to Y)$ is an
    equivalence.

    Further we have an induction principle, which similarly
    characterizes dependent functions into a family of $n$-types.
\end{definition}

The case of $-1$-truncation, otherwise known as propositional truncation, holds an important role in logic as well as in homotopy theory.
We think of $\Trunc{X}_{-1}$ as the proposition asking whether $X$ is inhabited.
Due to its importance we will often denote $-1$-truncation without the subscript, $\Trunc{X}$.

The case of $0$-truncation, a.k.a.\ set truncation, also corresponds to a common operation on spaces: The set $\setTrunc{X}$ is the set of path components of $X$.

\begin{definition}
    A type $X$ is \textbf{$n$-connected} if $\Trunc{X}_n$ is contractible.
\end{definition}

As special cases, we say that $X$ is \textbf{inhabited} (constructively
nonempty) if it's $-1$-connected, and \textbf{connected} if it's $0$-connected.
Every type is $-2$-connected, since $\Trunc{X}_{-2}$ is automatically contractible.

We have a corresponding notion of connectedness and truncatedness for maps defined fiberwise.
\begin{definition}
    A map $f : X \to Y$ is:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item \textbf{$n$-truncated} if for all $y : Y$, the type $\fib_f(y)$ is an $n$-type.
        \item \textbf{$n$-connected} if for all $y : Y$, the type $\fib_f(y)$ is $n$-connected.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

As special cases, a map $f:X\to Y$ is \textbf{surjective} if it's $-1$-connected
and an \textbf{embedding} if it's $-1$-truncated. For reasons we'll see later, we think of $0$-truncated maps as \textbf{set bundles}.
\begin{example}
    The map $\trunc{\blank}_n : X \to \Trunc{X}_n$ is $n$-connected.
\end{example}

\section{Path algebra}

Paths are the ``morphism'' part of the groupoid structure of types.
We can concatenate paths together when the endpoints agree, we can invert paths, and we have an identity path.

\begin{definition}
    Given $p : x = y$ and $q :  y = z$ in a type $X$, we define their \textbf{concatenation} $p \cdot q : x = z$ by path induction:
    \[  \refl_y \cdot q := q \]

    We can also define $p^{-1} : y = x$ by path induction:
    \[ (\refl_x)^{-1} := \refl_x \]
\end{definition}

These operations satisfy groupoid laws up to higher paths:
\begin{lemma}
    For any $p : x = y$, $q : y = z$ and $r : z = w$ we have terms of the following types:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item $p \cdot (q \cdot r) = (p \cdot q) \cdot r$,
        \item $p \cdot p^{-1} = \refl_y$ and $p^{-1} \cdot p = \refl_x$,
        \item $\refl_x \cdot p = p$ and $p \cdot \refl_y = p$.
    \end{itemize}
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
    All by path induction, and the definition of composition.
\end{proof}

Furthermore, every function forms a (higher) groupoid homomorphism.
\begin{definition}
    Given $f : X \to Y$ and $x_0, x_1 : X$ we obtain a map
    \begin{align*}
        \ap_f : x_0 =_X x_1 &\to f(x_0) =_Y f(x_1) \\
        \ap_f(\refl_{x_0}) &:= \refl_{f(x_0)}
    \end{align*}
    by path induction.
\end{definition}

This satisfies standard functoriality laws, again up to higher paths.
We've set it up so that definitionally the identity path is mapped to the other identity path.

\begin{lemma}
    Given $f : X \to Y$ and $p : x_0 = x_1$, $q : x_1 = x_2$ we have a term of type
    \[\ap_f(p \cdot q) = \ap_f(p) \cdot \ap_f(q)\]
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
    By path induction.
\end{proof}
%
This is a good place to recall the notion of dependent path.
%
Recall that we can define, by path induction, a map $\mathsf{coe} : A=B \to A \to B$.
%
\begin{definition}\label{def:dep-typ}
  Let $B : A \to \UU$ be a dependent type, and let $p : a_0 =_A a_1$ be a path in $A$. Given two terms $b_0 : B(a_0)$ and $b_1:B(a_1)$, we write $b_0=^B_p b_1$ for the the type of \textbf{dependent paths} (over $p$) between $b_0$ and $b_1$. It is defined by
  \[(b_0=^B_p b_1) := (\mathsf{coe}(\ap_B(p), b_0) = b_1)\]
\end{definition}
%
\begin{remark}
  There is a dependent version of $\ap_f$, often denoted $\apd_f$, where $f : (a:A) \to B(a))$ is a dependent function. It is of type $(p : a_0=_A a_1) \to a_0=^P_p a_1$ and is, like $\ap$, defined by path induction. Since these two definitions agree when $B$ is a constant family of types (i.e.\ a non-dependent type), we will abuse notation and write $\ap$ for both dependent and non-dependent function application.  
\end{remark}
%
The case when $B$ in \cref{def:dep-typ} is itself a path type is especially important.
\begin{definition}\label{def:fillers}
Consider the following square of paths:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fill}\begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=\&]
	z \& w \\
	x \& y
	\arrow["q", from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["r", from=2-1, to=1-1]
	\arrow["p"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow["s"', from=2-2, to=1-2]
\end{tikzcd}\end{equation}
A \textbf{filler} of \eqref{eq:fill} is a dependent path $p =_{(l,r)}^{(x,y)\mapsto x = y}q$.
\end{definition}
An alternative definition of the above would be to say that a filler of \eqref{eq:fill} is a path $p \cdot s =_{x = w} r \cdot q$. The advantage of the above definition is that it definitionally agrees with the usual identity type $(p= q)$ whenever $s$ and $r$ are $\refl$.
%
We obtain a notion of function application on squares by iterating (dependent) $\ap$, i.e.\ $\ap_{\ap_f}$.
%
We can mimic \cref{def:fillers} to define fillers of ($3$-)cubes, $4$-cubes, and so on.\footnote{There is, however no general definition of fillers of $n$-cubes. In fact, even defining an appropriate notion of $n$-cube is a long-standing open problem.} This is a good exercise but will not be needed for this course.
  

\section{Homotopy groups}

We now work towards defining the homotopy groups of a type.

\begin{definition}
    A \textbf{pointed type} is a pair $(X, x_0)$ where $X : \UU$ and $x_0 : X$. The collection of pointed types is
    $ \UU_{\bullet} := (X : \UU) \times (X)$.

    A morphism between two pointed types $(X, x_0)$ and $(Y, y_0)$ is a pair $(f, p)$ consisting of a map $f : X \to Y$ and a path $p : f(x_0) = y_0$.
    We denote the type of pointed maps as $(X, x_0) \to_\ast (Y, y_0)$
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}
    We have the \textbf{loop space} operation $\Omega : \UU_{\bullet} \to \UU_{\bullet}$ defined by
    \[ \Omega(X, x_0) := (x_0 =_X x_0, \refl_{x_0})\]
\end{definition}

We will often be imprecise when writing pointed types and loop spaces, dropping the notation of the point when it is clear.
In fact when a type is connected the choice of basepoint doesn't matter (up to mere equivalence), see the exercises.

The loop space is the fundamental structure which will allow us to define homotopy groups.
First note that the loop space is already ``group-like''.
Using path concatenation we get an operation $\_ \cdot \_ : \Omega(X, x_0) \to \Omega(X, x_0) \to \Omega(X, x_0)$.
This satisfies the usual group laws: path composition is associative, has unit $\refl_x$ and for each element $p$, it's inverse is $p^{-1}$.
The only thing that is preventing this from being a group is that it isn't a set!
These group laws only hold up to homotopy.
For instance there might be more than one element of $p \cdot p^{-1} = \refl_{x_0}$.
To solve this we set truncate everything to end up with an ordinary group.

\begin{definition}
    The \textbf{first homotopy group}, traditionally called the \textbf{fundamental group}, of a pointed type $(X, x_0)$ is
    \[ \pi_1(X, x_0) := \setTrunc{\Omega(X,x_0)}\]
\end{definition}

By set truncating we collapsed all of the higher loops of our type.
The higher homotopy groups are introduced to keep track of this higher homotopy information.

\begin{definition}
    The $n$\th loop space of $(X, x_0)$ is defined by recursion:
    \begin{align*}
        \Omega^0(X, x_0) &:= (X, x_0) \\
        \Omega^{n+1}(X, x_0) &:= \Omega(\Omega^{n}(X, x_0))
    \end{align*}

    The $n$\th homotopy group of $(X, x_0)$ is then:
    \[ \pi_n(X, x_0) := \setTrunc{\Omega^n(X, x_0)}\]
\end{definition}

Note all these operations are functorial: Given a pointed map $(f,q) : (X, x_0) \pto (Y, y_0)$ we get a map
\begin{align*}
    \Omega f : \Omega(X, x_0) &\pto \Omega(Y, y_0)  \\
    (\Omega f)(p)& := q\cdot \ap_f(p)\cdot q^{-1}
\end{align*}
which descends to a group homomorphism $\pi_n(X, x_0) \to \pi_n(Y, y_0)$ for each $n$ by truncation.

\section{The fundamental theorem of identity types}

Doing homotopy theory in HoTT is all about identity types, and so we need a good generic way to understand them.
A fundamental property of identity types is that given a fixed basepoint $x : X$ the type $(y : X) \times (x =_X y)$ is contractible onto $(x, \refl_x)$.
This is clear by path induction.

Even though this might seem like a trivial property, it is in fact a defining property, which the fundamental theorem makes clear.

\begin{theorem}[The Fundamental Theorem of Identity Types]
    Let $(X, x_0)$ be a pointed type and $Y : X \to \UU$ a type family.
    Suppose we have a function $f_x : x_0 =_X x \to Y(x)$ for all $x : X$.
    Then the following are equivalent:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item $f$ is a family of equivalences.
        \item The total space $(x : X) \times Y(x)$ is contractible.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

As an example, let us characterize the identity types of dependent sums. If $Y:X\to\UU$ is a type family over $X$ with a fixed element $(x_0,y_0):(x:X)\times Y(x)$ of the type space,
define $P:\bigl((x:X)\times Y(x)\bigr) \to \UU$ by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:dep-sum}
  P(x,y) := (p : x_0=_X x) \times (p_* y_0 =_{Y(x)} y).
\end{equation}
We can show that the total space is contractible by twice contracting a singleton:
\begin{align*}
  &(x:X)\times(y:Y(x))\times P(x,y)\\
  \simeq\;
  &(x:X)\times(y:Y(x))\times(p : x_0=_X x)\times(p_*y_0 =_{Y(x)}y)\\
  \simeq\;
  &(y:Y(x_0))\times(\refl_{x_0*}y_0 = y)
  \simeq 1
\end{align*}

This in turn can be used to establish the following important characterization of type families,
sometimes known as \textbf{straightening--unstraightening}.
\begin{theorem}
  For any small type $X:\UU$, forming the dependent sum along with the first projection gives an equivalence:
  \[
    (X \to \UU) \simeq \Bigl((Y : \UU) \times (Y \to X)\Bigr)
  \]
\end{theorem}
The inverse maps a type over $X$, $f : Y\to X$, to the family of fibers, $\fib_f$.

\section{Exercises}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Show that for $n \geq m$ and any type $A$ we have
    \[ \Trunc{\Trunc{A}_n}_m \simeq \Trunc{A}_m. \]

  \item\label{ex:n-conn-orth}
    Show that a type $X$ is $n$-connected if and only if, for every $n$-type $Y$,
    the diagonal map
    \[ Y \to (X \to Y), \quad y\mapsto (x\mapsto y),
    \]
    is an equivalence.

  \item Show that the map $\trunc\blank_n : X \to \Trunc X_n$ is $n$-connected.

    \item Consider a map $f : X \to Y$.
      We define its \textbf{$n$-image} to be the type $\im_n(f) :=
      (y : Y) \times \Trunc{\fib_f(y)}_n$.
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item Show that we can factorise $f$ through the $n$-image, that is,
      construct a commuting diagram:
        \[\begin{tikzcd}
            X \ar[rr, "f"] \ar[dr, swap, "p"] & & Y \\
            & \im_n(f) \ar[ur, swap, "i"]
        \end{tikzcd}\]
    \item Show that $p$ is $n$-connected and $i$ is $n$-truncated.
    \item Show that if $Z$ is any type, $g : X \to Z$ is $n$-connected, and $h:Z\to Y$ is $n$-truncated with $f = h\circ g$, then there is a unique equivalence $e : \im_n(f) \to Z$ with $e\circ p = g$ and $h\circ e = i$:
      \[
        \begin{tikzcd}
      & Z \ar[dr,"h"] & \\
