\chapter{A menagerie of higher inductive types}

\section{The circle}

A higher inductive type is like a normal inductive type, where instead of just being able to specify points of the type, we can also specify paths between points, paths between paths, and so on.
For example, take the circle, which we define as follows.
\begin{definition}
    The \textbf{circle} is the HIT generated by
    \begin{align*}
        \ast &: S^1 \\
        \Sloop &: \ast = \ast
    \end{align*}
\end{definition}
This type comes with universal properties as normal inductive types do.
In this case the recursion principle tells us that to define a map $S^1 \to X$ it's enough to give a point $x : X$ and a path $x =_X x$. More precisely, the evaluation map
\[
  (S^1 \to X) \to (x : X) \times (x=_X x),
  \quad
  f \mapsto (f(\ast), \ap_f(\Sloop)),
\]
is an equivalence. From this we deduce also an induction principle for type families $p : S^1 \to \UU$. Here we encounter again a ``dependent path'' ($\Sloop_*(x) =_{P(\ast)} x$). The map
\[
  \Bigl((z : S^1) \to P(z)\Bigr) \to \Bigl(x : P(\ast) \times (\Sloop_*(x)
  =_{P(\ast)} x)\Bigr),
  \quad f \mapsto (f(\ast), \ap_f(\Sloop))
\]
is an
equivalence.

We can visualise the circle as one would normally, $\ast$ is the basepoint and and $\mathrm{loop}$ as a loop drawn from the basepoint to itself.

