\chapter[The Hopf fibration and the LES]{The Hopf fibration and the long exact sequence}

\section{The fundamental group of the circle}

With the tools we have built up, we can now recreate a very classical result, that $\pi_1(S^1) = \ZZ$.
We do this in the usual way, by constructing the universal cover of the circle.
Consider the type family:
\begin{align*}
    R : S^1 &\to \UU \\
    R(\ast) &:= \ZZ \\
    \ap_R(\Sloop) &:= ( \_ + 1 )
\end{align*}
where we consider $\_ + 1 : \ZZ = \ZZ$ by univalence.

This cover looks like a homotopy theoretic version of the real numbers, wound up in a helix over the circle.
Over each point in the circle we have a copy of the integers, and rotating around the circle once, increases the integer in the cover.
You can imagine unwinding a loop that goes round the origin $n$ times, to a segment $[0, n]$ (or $[n,0]$ for negative $n$) in the real numbers.
Our goal now is to show that this type family actually corresponds to the identity types on the circle.
To do this we will use the fundamental theorem of the identity types.
It's sensible to expect this to work, since our picture of $R$ is the real line, which is contractible.

To start with there is an obvious map $\ast = x \to R(x)$ for $x : S^1$
given by path induction sending $\refl_\ast$ to $0 : \ZZ$.
Now our goal is to show the total space $(x : S^1) \times R(x)$ is contractible.
The centre of contraction we choose is $(\ast, 0)$.
Hence our goal is to show for all $x : S^1$, and $y : R(x)$ we have $(\ast, 0) = (x, y)$.
By our characterisation of identity types of dependent sums~\eqref{eq:dep-sum}, this type is equivalent to $(p : \ast =_{S^1} x) \times (p_*0 =_{R(x)} y)$.
By $S^1$-induction, since the second component is a proposition, this is the same as constructing a function
$h : \ZZ \to (\ast =_{S^1} \ast)$
satisfying $h(k)_*(0) = k$ for all $k$, together with
a proof
$H : {\Sloop}_*(h) = h$.
To construct this proof, it will be helpful to generalise the situation to apply path induction.

\begin{lemma}
\label{lem:trp-fun}
    Let $P,Q : X \to \UU$ and $p : x_0 =_X x_1$.
    Let $f : P(x_0) \to Q(x_0)$.
    Then we can identify $p_*(f) : P(x_1) \to Q(x_1)$ with the composition
    \[ Q(p) \circ f \circ P(p)^{-1} : P(x_1) \to Q(x_1).\]
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  By path induction.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
    The total space $(x : S^1) \times R(x)$ is contractible.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  First we construct $h : (k : \ZZ) \to (\ast =_{S^1} \ast)$
  by integer induction as the power $h(k) := \Sloop^k$.
  This indeed satisfies $h(k)_*(0) = (\Sloop^k)_*(0) = k$, as desired.

  Next we show ${\Sloop}_*(h) = h$.
  To apply~\cref{lem:trp-fun} it's important to realize that we're transporting in the family of types $R(x) \to (\ast =_{S^1} x)$ for $x:S^1$. Now we have
  \[ \Sloop_*(h) = (\blank \cdot \Sloop) \circ h \circ (\blank-1),\]
  which maps $k:\ZZ$ to $\Sloop^{k-1}\cdot\Sloop$, which indeed equals $h(k)=\Sloop^k$.

  Hence by the discussion above $(x : S^1) \times R(x)$ is contractible.
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}\label{cor:id-S1}
    The family of maps $\ast = x \to R(x)$ is a family of equivalences.
    Hence $\Omega(S^1,\ast) \simeq \ZZ$.
\end{corollary}
\begin{proof}
    Immediate from the previous lemma and the fundamental theorem of identity types
\end{proof}
Note also that by construction, this equivalence is an equivalence of groups.

\begin{corollary}
    $\pi_1(S^1) = \ZZ$ and $\pi_n(S^1) = 0$ for all $n > 1$.
\end{corollary}
\begin{proof}
    We have
    \[ \pi_1(S^1) := \Trunc{\Omega S^1}_0 = \Trunc{\ZZ}_0 = \ZZ \]
    and for $n > 1$ we note $\Omega^n S^1 = \Omega^{n-1} \ZZ = 1$ since $\ZZ$ is a set.
    Thus as a group $\pi_n(S^1)$ is trivial.
\end{proof}

\section{Multiplying points on the circle}

We start our view into the world of higher homotopy types by having a closer look at the circle. It is a $1$-type, so under the homotopy hypothesis (identifying types and $\infty$-groupoids), it corresponds to a groupoid. We shall see in three ways that it carries a multiplication. It is the homotopical abstraction of the group of rotations in the plane, $\mathrm{SO(2)}$, or equivalently, the group of unit complex numbers, $\mathrm{U(1)} = \{\,z:\mathbb{C}^2 \mid \abs z=1\,\}$.

For the first, we can ``by hand'' define the product operation $\_ \cdot \_ : S^1 \to S^1 \to S^1$. (Exercise)

For the second, let us think about $S^1$ as a groupoid of structured objects. (This is how we first encounter many groupoids or categories, as structured sets, such as groups, rings, partial orders, etc.)

Finally, we shall see that $S^1$ is itself the loop space of a pointed type, so we have
an induced multiplication corresponding to composition of loops.

\begin{definition}
  The type of sets with an endomorphism is $\SetEndo := (X : \Set) \times (X \to X)$.
\end{definition}
Use univalence to verify that this is a groupoid.

We have a map $\varphi : S^1 \to \SetEndo$ whose first component at $z : S^1$ is
the identity type $\ast = z$ and whose second component is the map $\_ \cdot \Sloop : (\ast = z) \to (\ast = z)$ that composes with the loop.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:S1-InfCyc}
  The map $\varphi : S^1 \to \SetEndo$ is an embedding, so it induces an equivalence
  from $S^1$ to its image.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
  Consider the diagram:
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:setbundle-Sc-univ-comp}
  \begin{tikzcd}
    & S^1\ar[dl,"{(1,\cst_\ast)}"']\ar[d]\ar[dr,"\varphi"] & \\
    \bigl((X:\UU)\times(X\to S^1)\bigr)_{(1,\cst_\ast)} \ar[r,"\sim"']
    & (S^1\to\UU)_{(\ast=\blank)} \ar[r,"\sim"']
    & \im(\varphi)
  \end{tikzcd}
\end{equation}
To show $\varphi$ is an equivalence, it suffices to show the map on the left is
an equivalence, but that is easy.

Alternatively, we show that the middle vertical map is an equivalence, which follows from the \emph{type theoretic Yoneda lemma}: The identity type gives an embedding $X \hookrightarrow (X \to \UU)$, $x\mapsto (x' \mapsto x=_Xx')$.
\end{proof}
Using~\cref{cor:id-S1} we can identify $\varphi(\ast)$ as the set of integers
$\ZZ$ with the successor map $\suc : \ZZ \to \ZZ$.

\begin{definition}
  The type of $\ZZ$-torsors (relative to the generating element $1:\ZZ$), $\Tors_\ZZ$,
  is the connected component of $\SetEndo$ at $(\ZZ,\suc)$.
\end{definition}
So another way to state the theorem is that $\varphi$ induces an equivalence
$S^1 \simeq \Tors_\ZZ$. In this form, $\ZZ$-torsors are also known as \textbf{infinite cycles}.
See the exercises for how this gives another way of looking at the multiplication on the circle.

\bigskip

Finally, we can improve the multiplication on the circle by exhibiting it as coming from composition of loops in another type. That is, we can find a pointed (1-connected) type $\B^2\ZZ$ and a pointed equivalence $S^1 \simeq_\bullet \Omega\B^2\ZZ$.
In fact, we even have different ways of defining $\B^2\ZZ$:
\begin{enumerate}
\item We can take $\B^2\ZZ := \Trunc{S^2}_2$.
\item We can take $\B^2\ZZ := (X : \UU) \times \setTrunc{X\simeq S^1}$.
\item We can take $\B^2\ZZ := (X : \UU) \times \Trunc{X} \times
  \bigl((x : X) \to S^1 \simeq_\bullet (X,x)\bigr)$.
\end{enumerate}

Once we have the LES we get $\pi_2(S^2) = \pi_1(S^1) = \ZZ$. This gives that $\Trunc{S^2}_2$ is a delooping of $S^1$. The second equivalence comes from an equivalence $(S^1\to S^1) \simeq (\ZZ \times S^1)$, from which we get that evaluation at $\ast$ is an equivalence:
\[
  \bigl((e : S^1 \simeq S^1) \times \Trunc{e = \id}\bigr)
  \simeq S^1.
\]

\section{The Hopf fibration}

\begin{definition}
  We define a type family $H : S^2 \to \UU$ by induction:
  \begin{align*}
    H(N) &:= H(S) := S^1 \\
    \ap_H(\merid_z) &:= (z \cdot \blank)
  \end{align*}
\end{definition}
Here we are using univalence implicitly to regard multiplication by $z$ as an identification $z \cdot\blank:S^1 = S^1$.

In fact, we can do the same construction for any \textbf{left-invertible H-space},
meaning a pointed type $A$ with a multiplication $\blank\cdot\blank:A\to A\to A$ s.t.\
$a\cdot\pt = \pt\cdot a=a$ for all $a:A$, and $a\cdot\blank : A \to A$ is an equivalence for each $a:A$. We get $H : \Sigma A \to \UU$
with $H(N) = H(S) = A$ and $\ap_H(\merid_a) = (a\cdot\blank)$.

We would like to identify the total space of such a family. This is exactly what is provided by the flattening lemma. We'll just state it for now, and defer the proof to~\cref{ch:pushouts}.
\begin{lemma}[Flattening lemma]
  Given a span $\begin{tikzcd}[cramped]
    A & C\ar[l,"f"']\ar[r,"g"] & B
  \end{tikzcd}$ with pushout $D$ and a type family $P : D \to \UU$ defined by
  \begin{align*}
    P_{\inl} &: A \to \UU \\
    P_{\inr} &: B \to \UU \\
    P_{\glue} &: (c:C) \to P_{\inl}(f(c)) \simeq P_{\inr}(g(c)),
  \end{align*}
  the total space of $P$ is equivalent to the pushout of the span
  \[
    \begin{tikzcd}
      \bigl((a:A)\times P_{\inl}(a)\bigr) &
      \bigl((c:C)\times P_{\inl}(f(c))\bigr) \ar[l]\ar[r] &
      \bigl((b:B)\times P_{\inr}(b)\bigr),
    \end{tikzcd}
  \]
  where the left maps is $(c,u)\mapsto(f(c),u)$ and the right map is
  $(c,u)\mapsto(g(c),P_{\glue}(c)(u))$.
\end{lemma}

Since the suspension $\Sigma A$ is the pushout of the span $1 \leftarrow A \to 1$,
this applies to the family $H$, and we conclude that the total space $(z:\Sigma A)\times H(z)$
is the pushout of the span at the top of the following map of spans:
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge]
    A\ar[d,"\id"'] & A \times A\ar[l,"\fst"'] \ar[r,"{(a,b)\mapsto a\cdot b}"]
    \ar[d,"{(a,b)\mapsto (a,a\cdot b)}"] & A\ar[d,"\id"] \\
    A & A\times A\ar[l,"\fst"']\ar[r,"\snd"] & A
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
Since the vertical maps are equivalences, the pushouts are equivalent, so the total space is equivalent to $A*A$.
\begin{corollary}
  For the Hopf fibration $H: S^2 \to \UU$, the total space can be identified with $S^3$.
\end{corollary}
\begin{proof}
  Use $S^1*S^1 = S^3$ from~\cref{cor:Sn-join-Sm}.
\end{proof}

\section{The long exact sequence}

For any pointed map $f : E \pto B$ we get a long exact sequence of homotopy groups:
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}
    & \cdots\ar[r] & \pi_{n+1}(B) \ar[dll] \\
    \pi_n(F)\ar[r] & \pi_n(E)\ar[r] & \pi_n(B) \ar[dll] \\
    \pi_{n-1}(F)\ar[r] & \cdots &\\
    &\cdots\ar[r] & \pi_1(B) \ar[dll] \\
    \pi_0(F)\ar[r] & \pi_0(E)\ar[r] & \pi_0(B)
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
where $F:=\fib_f(\bullet)$ is the fiber of $f$ and the arrows are homomorphisms of groups until
$\pi_1(B)$, and then maps of pointed sets.
Exactness means that the image of a map equals the kernel of the next.

We construct this in several steps:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Form the untruncated fiber sequence: We have the fiber map $\Phi : (E,B:\UU_\bullet)\times(E \pto B) \to (E,B:\UU_\bullet)\times(E\pto B)$ given by $(E,B,f) \mapsto (\fib_f(\bullet), E, \fst)$.
  Thus we can iterate an get a sequence $\Phi^n(E,B,f)$ for any $n:\NN$.
\item Construct an equivalence to
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}
    & \cdots\ar[r] & \Omega^{n+1}(B) \ar[dll] \\
    \Omega^n(F)\ar[r] & \Omega^n(E)\ar[r] & \Omega^n(B) \ar[dll] \\
    \Omega^{n-1}(F)\ar[r] & \cdots &\\
    &\cdots\ar[r] & \Omega(B) \ar[dll] \\
    F\ar[r] & E\ar[r] & B
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
For this, we note that $F^2(E,B,f) = (\Omega B, F, \delta)$,
where $\delta : \Omega B \pto F$ maps a loop $p$ to $p_*(\bullet)$.
\item Set-truncate at the end.
\end{enumerate}
Applied to the Hopf fiber sequence $S^1 \to S^3 \to S^2$, we get the long exact sequence ending with:
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}
    & \cdots\ar[r] & \pi_{n+1}(S^2) \ar[dll] \\
    0\ar[r] & \pi_n(S^3)\ar[r] & \pi_n(S^2) \ar[dll] \\
    0\ar[r] & \cdots &\\
    &\cdots\ar[r] & \pi_4(S^2) \ar[dll]\ar[dll]  \\
    0\ar[r] & \pi_3(S^3)\ar[r] & \pi_3(S^2)\ar[dll]  \\
    0\ar[r] & 0\ar[r] & \pi_2(S^2)\ar[dll]  \\
    \ZZ\ar[r] & 0\ar[r] & 0\ar[dll]  \\
    0\ar[r] & 0\ar[r] & 0
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
We conclude that $\pi_2(S^2)\simeq \ZZ$ and $\pi_n(S^3)\simeq\pi_n(S^2)$ for $n\ge 3$.

